So, I missed World Burlesque Day yesterday.
In my 15 year career, I guess I've never quite done burlesque right. I've been told I'm a "burlesque and..." performer. Started off tapping-and-stipping and now I'm incorporating swords. I wore a corset on stage for the very first time this year (by no choice of my own 🤣) and I did my first feather fan dance just two years ago, but only with one fan and with a sword attached to it. 🤷‍♀️

But I am so grateful for have had the opportunity to grow up in the burlesque world alongside the other sparkly misfits and weirdos. I've found a family that I couldn't imagine being without. Thanks for embracing this little variety performer. 💖

And thanks @vnat1988 for the capture. Please watch until the end. 😂

After 14 months, 162 shows, 3 months of rehearsals and tech, and who knows how many dress rehearsals, it's my last weekend at @cocktailmagique. 🥲

I'm sure I'll have more to say later, but for now here's a glimpse into the behind the scenes of this clown family that we've built over the last year. I could've made a reel with footage of @emstockwell alone, but I tried to include everyone in there. 😂

Here's to a great last weekend of shows! 🥂✨💋

And just like that, @cocktailmagique 2.0 took their final bows last night. 💖

I cannot believe that a year has already passed! I am so incredibly grateful to have been a part of this amazing show filled with supremely talented, intelligent, hilarious, and kind weirdos, both on stage and behind the scenes. I love this family that we built. 🥰

I'm going to miss being bathed in @briantovardesign 's incredible lighting and being adorned in @zanepihlstromdesigns' s stunning frocks every week. Thank you @austinmccormickxiv for bringing me into your beautiful world and giving me a stage to be gross and glamorous and stupid all in one show.

If you're ever near Reading, PA, don't miss out on visiting this 1892 gem!

A little photo dump from my weekend at @gables_stirling. 🥰

Named after Stirling Castle in Scotland, the home was built in 1892 by steel magnate J. H. Sternbergh. The home was kept in the family until 1996, used not only as a home, but also as place to hold art shows, salons, and charity events. Now the home has been lovingly preserved by the folks of @gablesbb, who opened up the mansion for weddings, overnight guests, and, in the spirit of the Sternberghs, annual charity events benefitting the local communtiy.

If you're ever near Reading, PA don't miss this gem! The money from your stay helps keep their charity afloat. 💗
